		<header>
			
			<h1>European Parliament votes for ‘fair, transparent and sustainable trade in fish’  </h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 August 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The European Parliament has passed a resolution on the arrangements for importing fishery and aquaculture products into the EU, with an eye to the reform of the CFP. In its general considerations, the resolution notes that ‘EU fishery and aquaculture production falls well short of the needs of the processing industry and growing consumer demand, and will continue to do so’ and acknowledges ‘the need to promote responsible consumption, based upon quality and sustainability rather than quantity’. The resolution makes specific reference to trade and customs policy; environmental, social, health and quality aspects; the revision of the Common Organisation of the Markets (CMO), consumer information and aquaculture.</p><p>On trade and customs policy, the resolution highlights that, ‘although fishery and aquaculture products continue to receive a level of theoretical customs protection, in practice this protection is significantly diminished by various exemptions and reductions, meaning that imports actually subject to MFN tariffs (applicable by default) account for about 5% of the total.’ It further notes that ‘the policy to open up EU markets for fishery and aquaculture imports is likely to continue ... The conclusion of the Doha Round NAMA talks on the basis of the “Swiss formula” as currently envisaged would reduce the maximum customs tariff applicable to fishery and aquaculture products in the EU from 26% to about 6% and the average tariff from 12% to about 5% ... Such a decision, as well as almost completely negating the protective effect of the tariffs still in place, would seriously erode the preferences already granted to developing countries ... The Parliament therefore demands that fishery and aquaculture products be treated as sensitive products for the purposes of applying the “Swiss formula” in the WTO’s Doha Round NAMA talks to preserve the value of the preferences granted to some partners and the effectiveness of CMO mechanisms.’</p><p>This chapter of the resolution also underlines that ‘the EU's requirement for coherence between its development policy objectives (eliminating poverty, development of sustainable local fisheries) and its trade policy implies that developing countries should be encouraged to export fisheries products with a greater added value, provided that the fish comes from well-managed and sustainable fisheries and meets the necessary sanitary conditions.’</p><p>The resolution further emphasises that the EU needs to retain control over the trade preferences that it grants to certain partners by insisting on the application of strict rules of origin based on the concept of ‘wholly obtained’ products. More generally, one of the key aims of EU policy on fishery and aquaculture imports should be to ensure that imported products meet the same requirements that apply to EU production in every respect. In that context, the Parliament asks the Commission to use all the tools available to ensure that the main countries exporting fishery and aquaculture products to the EU fulfil the undertakings given in Johannesburg and apply rigorous policies to conserve stocks, and demands that all the trade preferences granted by the EU in respect of fishery and aquaculture products be made strictly conditional upon the fulfilment of stringent environmental and social requirements – provisions to this effect in agreements concluded should include credible mechanisms for monitoring compliance with the undertakings given and for suspending the preferences, or simply withdrawing them, if the undertakings are breached. In the case of developing countries, it calls for the implementation of programmes specifically designed to grant technical support, and financial support if necessary, in order to help the affected states to respect their social and environmental commitments.</p><p>The resolution emphasises that it is absolutely essential to address the reality of fierce competition from low-cost imports resulting from practices that are damaging to the environment or equivalent to a form of social dumping.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
European Parliament resolution of 8 July 2010 on the arrangements for importing fishery and aquaculture products into the EU with a view to the future reform of the CFP<br />
<a href="http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?language=EN&amp;reference=A7-0207/2010" target="_self">http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?language=EN&amp;reference=...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>This European Parliament report is amongst the first to be adopted since the Lisbon Treaty came into force. This gives the European Parliament the power to ‘co-decide’ with the Council of Ministers. Previously the Parliament only had a consultative role on fisheries matters. It is incumbent on the EC to take note of this report, implement its recommendations in the reform of the CMO for fisheries and aquaculture products. </p><p>For ACP countries, this report contains good and bad news. On the one side, the report puts a strong emphasis on the protection of EU producers, consumers and processing industries, rather than on developing countries’ interests. However, it also acknowledges that tariff protection is the key aspect of the preferences granted by the EU to some developing countries, such as those in the ACP, and abolishing that protection would deprive these countries benefiting from preferences of all the advantages they have. Concerning the way forward, it needs to be noted that, in many cases, the main competitors of both EU-produced and ACP-produced fish are the low-cost products from non-ACP countries. There may be similar interests between ACP and EU producers to highlight the nutritional, environmental and social qualities of their products to address such competition by low-cost, low-quality products.</p>
		</div>
		
